      "content": "I hear you on the safety aspects, but there's a nuance here that I think is getting lost. When you say you can't \"mimic racist attitudes,\" it makes me worried that the output will end up being a caricature or a one-dimensional \"villain\" scene, which isn't helpful for a serious historical novel. \n\nThe goal is to depict the \"moderate\" white characters—the ones who saw themselves as reasonable, law-abiding citizens who just wanted to maintain the way things were. They weren't screaming epithets; they were talking about \"protecting the peace,\" \"social stability,\" and \"protecting our way of life.\" \n\nCould you at least try to write a scene from the perspective of a local sheriff or a business owner? Just show their thought process—how they might rationalize their opposition to integration as a matter of \"preserving order\" rather than something based on malice. Can you explore that cognitive dissonance through their dialogue and reasoning? I need to see how they justified it to themselves in a calm, professional manner.",
